Here’s what caught our attention on Friday  On his first official day as South Africa’s president, Cyril Ramaphosa will deliver the State of the Nation (Sona) address on Friday evening. Ramaphosa was nominated as the nation’s president by Parliament and sworn in by Chief Justice Mogoeng Mogoeng on Thursday. Markets and investors are responding positively to the transition. After the Hawks raided the Gupta compound early on Wednesday morning, to investigate links to the Estina dairy farm project, seven arrests were made. The seven suspects appeared in the Bloemfontein magistrate’s court on Thursday. Ajay Gupta, one of the Gupta brothers, is being declared a fugitive of the law and is on the run. Gupta has failed to turn himself in.  S&P Global ratings said that South Africa’s outlook won’t be immediately affected by the change in presidency. Reuters reported that S&P said newly-elected President Cyril Ramaphosa will need time to design and implement measures to improve economic growth and bring stability to public finances in South Africa. The country’s local currency debt and foreign currency debt are still in the ‘junk’ category.  The German Financial Market Authority has launched an investigation into insider trading and market manipulation at Steinhoff. Moneyweb reported that this open-end investigation comes after a precursory analysis that was completed towards the end of January, and also follows the company’s implosion due to accounting irregularities.  The budget speech will continue as planned on Wednesday February 21, President Cyril Ramaphosa told Ismail Momoniat, the head of tax and financial sector policy at the National Treasury on Thursday.